{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539040"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:36:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:36:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16426"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16426"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.1,0.1,0.46,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9117"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113304"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9117"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95339"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1359"},{"type":"tags","id":"1507"},{"type":"tags","id":"4154"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49330"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113304"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with vaginal bleeding and severe cramping abdominal pain for three hours. She believes she is approximately nine weeks pregnant based on her last menstrual period. She has no significant medical history and takes only folate supplements. On examination, she appears distressed and clammy. Her pulse rate is 42/min, blood pressure 80/45 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is tender in the suprapubic region. Speculum examination reveals products of conception protruding through a dilated cervical os.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate removal of products with sponge forceps","Administration of atropine","Transfer to operating theatre","Intravenous fluid resuscitation","Urgent ultrasound scan"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with cervical shock, a vasovagal response that occurs when products of conception become trapped in the cervical os during a miscarriage. The characteristic features are bradycardia and hypotension due to vagal stimulation from cervical stretching.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate removal of products with sponge forceps\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step as it removes the stimulus causing the vasovagal response. Most patients show rapid improvement in vital signs once the products are removed from the cervical os.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous fluid resuscitation\u003C/strong\u003E alone will not address the underlying cause of the shock and will take some time to initiate. While fluids may be needed if the shock persists after addressing the cause, removing the cervical stimulus takes priority and often leads to rapid improvement without the need for further intervention. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eatropine\u003C/strong\u003E can treat bradycardia, it does not address the underlying cause. Moreover, the bradycardia will usually resolve spontaneously once the products are removed from the cervical os. It would be administered if the shock continues after addressing the underlying cause of if this cannot be adequately addressed immediately. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent ultrasound scan\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary before removing visible products from the cervical os in a patient with cervical shock. The immediate priority is to remove the stimulus causing cardiovascular compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to operating theatre\u003C/strong\u003E may eventually be needed for surgical management of the miscarriage, but the immediate priority is to reverse the cervical shock by removing visible products at the bedside.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter removal of products and stabilisation of vital signs, further assessment and management of the miscarriage can proceed. This may include ultrasound to confirm complete evacuation and potential need for surgical completion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cervical shock can occur when products of conception are trapped in the cervical os, causing vagal stimulation and cardiovascular collapse.","Immediate removal of products from the cervical os is essential to reverse cervical shock.","After removal of products, patients usually recover quickly without need for additional interventions."],"references":["Bellomo T. Vaginal bleeding and miscarriage [Internet]. Life in the Fast Lane; 2023 [cited 2024 Nov 25]. Available from: https://litfl.com/vaginal-bleeding-miscarriage/","Birch JD, Gulati D, Mandalia S. Cervical shock: a complication of incomplete abortion. BMJ Case Rep. 2017 Jul 14;2017:bcr2017220452. doi: 10.1136/bcr-2017-220452. PMID: 28710197; PMCID: PMC5535053."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95339"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16426"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95339"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-11T12:14:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-11T12:15:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9117"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113304"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1359"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Shock","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-09-17T03:13:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-30T17:26:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"m